The '''Molecularium Project''' is an informal [[science education]] project of [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpi.edu/magazine/march2009/stealth_education.html |title=Rensselaer Magazine March 2009 - "Stealth Education" |publisher=Rpi.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>  The Molecularium Project introduces young audiences to the world of [[atoms]] and [[molecules]] using character driven stories, immersive animation, interactive games and activities, and state of the art molecular visualizations.  [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute|Rensselaer]]'s three principal Scientist / Educators behind the project are [[Dr. Linda S. Schadler]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://faculty.rpi.edu/node/1080 |title=Linda S. Schadler &#124; Faculty Interest Inventory |publisher=Faculty.rpi.edu |date=2011-02-22 |accessdate=2012-07-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726000039/http://faculty.rpi.edu/node/1080 |archive-date=2012-07-26 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> Dr. [[Richard W. Siegel]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eng.rpi.edu/soe/index.php/faculty/154?soeid=sieger |title=Faculty Member |publisher=Eng.rpi.edu |date=2009-08-18 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> and Dr. [[Shekhar Garde]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eng.rpi.edu/soe/index.php/faculty/154?soeid=gardes |title=Faculty Member |publisher=Eng.rpi.edu |date=2009-08-18 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>  The Molecularium Project began as an outreach project of Rensselaer's Nanoscale Science and Engineering Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpi.edu/dept/nsec/04_01_05-primary.html |title=NSF NSEC for Directed Assembly of Nanostructures |publisher=Rpi.edu |date=2005-02-04 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>  To realize the productions, the scientists employed the creative team Nanotoon Entertainment, led by writer/director [[V. Owen Bush]], and writer/producer Kurt Przybilla. The Molecularium Project is funded by [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute|Rensselaer]], the [[National Science Foundation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nsf.gov/news/now_showing/more/molecularium.jsp |title=US NSF - Now Showing: Molecularium |publisher=Nsf.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> and [[New York State]].

== Productions ==

=== Pilot Show ===

In 2002, Dr. Schadler and Dr. Garde  produced a seven-minute pilot show for the local [[planetarium]] called “Molecularium” for the [[Digistar II]] Planetarium system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.rpi.edu/update.do?artcenterkey=217 |title=RPI: News & Events - What Really Matters: Rensselaer, Junior Museum, and NSF Open the "Molecularium" |publisher=News.rpi.edu |date=2002-12-11 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>  It introduces children to the concepts of atoms and molecules from small molecules like [[H2O]] to larger molecules like [[polymers]].

=== Molecularium - Riding Snowflakes ===

<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Molecularium1.jpg|thumb|right]] -->

In early 2004, Schadler, Garde, and Siegel were awarded a U.S. [[National Science Foundation]] grant to make a new Molecularium show exclusively for the [[fulldome]] medum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nsf.gov/news/news_summ.jsp?cntn_id=101824 |title=National Science Foundation (NSF) News - Presenting the Molecularium - US National Science Foundation (NSF) |publisher=nsf.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> They recruited the filmmaker and experience designer [[V. Owen Bush]] to bring the idea to life. Bush founded the production company Nanotoon Entertainment with writer/producer Kurt Przybilla to realize the new project. Bush and Przybilla proposed an adventure story of personified atoms flying a ship called the Molecularium through nanoscale materials including a snowflake, a penny, a stick of gum and the human body.

In February 2005, the team debuted "Molecularium - Riding Snowflakes" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://pubs.acs.org/cen/education/84/8417kids.html |title=Chemical & Engineering News: Education - Kids And Cartoons |publisher=Pubs.acs.org |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswise.com/articles/view/515452/ |title=ACS President Views Molecularium(tm) as Part of National Chemistry Week |publisher=Newswise.com |date=2005-10-19 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> a 23-minute digital planetarium show at the [[Children's Museum of Science and Technology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redorbit.com/news/science/139164/molecule_movie_offers_new_twist_for_kids/ |title=Molecule Movie Offers New Twist for Kids - Science News |publisher=redOrbit |date=2005-03-28 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.rpi.edu/update.do?artcenterkey=925&skinNameSticky=default |title=RPI: News & Events - Rensselaer’s Molecularium  Show Premieres |publisher=News.rpi.edu |date=2005-02-04 |accessdate=2012-07-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527214643/http://news.rpi.edu/update.do?artcenterkey=925&skinNameSticky=default |archive-date=2010-05-27 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> In 2005, "Molecularium - Riding Snowflakes" won the Domie at Domefest in Albuquerque New Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.domefest.org/domie-award-winners/ |title=Past Domie Winners |publisher=Domefest.org |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=scarr at April 7, 2006 11:03 AM |url=http://www.unm.edu/~market/cgi-bin/archives/001167.html |title=UNM Today: LodeStar turns inward to become 'Molecularium' |publisher=Unm.edu |date=2006-04-07 |accessdate=2012-07-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120704011000/http://www.unm.edu/~market/cgi-bin/archives/001167.html |archive-date=2012-07-04 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> "Molecularium - Riding Snowflakes" has shown at [[Chabot Space and Science Center]] in Oakland Ca., the [[Newark Museum]] Planetarium in Newark, NJ, Dubai Children’s City, UAE, and [[Thinktank, Birmingham]], UK, among many other digital planetariums.  It has been translated and versioned in [[Arabic]], [[Korean language|Korean]] and [[Turkish language|Turkish]].  It is Distributed by [[Evans and Sutherland|E&S]], [[Spitz]], Sky-Skan, and e-Planetarium.

In 2010, the [[American Library Association]] (ALA) selected the Molecularium Kid's Site for inclusion to its Great Websites for Kids.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gws.ala.org/content/molecularium |title=Molecularium &#124; Great Websites for Kids |publisher=Gws.ala.org |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709233215/http://gws.ala.org/content/molecularium |archive-date=2012-07-09 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>

=== Molecularium - Molecules to the MAX! ===

Molecules to the MAX!<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1813512/</ref> is a 41-minute fully animated [[Stereoscopy|3D]] [[IMAX]] film for the [[70 mm film#IMAX|Giant Screen]].  The film re-imagines the characters and story developed for "Molecularium- Riding Snowflakes" for an older audience and a different medium.  The film's simulations and rendering were partially computed at the [[Computational Center for Nanotechnology Innovations]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ghose |first=Tia |url=http://classic.the-scientist.com/news/display/55508/ |title=Molecules to the Max - The Scientist - Magazine of the Life Sciences |publisher=Classic.the-scientist.com |date=2009-03-13 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> The film was produced by Nanotoon Entertainment and Developed at [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute|Rensselaer]], with a gift from [[Curtis R. Priem]], co-founder of [[Nvidia]] corporation.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nature |url=http://www.nature.com/news/2010/100526/full/465416a.html |title=Science funding: Science for the masses : Nature News |publisher=Nature.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref><ref>http://www.moleculestothemax.com/Images/LFEaxminer/LFEaxminer_MakingMolecules.pdf{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.nanowerk.com/news/newsid=7167.php |title=Newest Molecularium movie: 'Molecules to the MAX' |publisher=Nanowerk.com |date=2008-09-09 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>

The digital version of the film premiered at [[EMPAC]], in Troy, NY on Feb. 27, 2009.  The [[70 mm film#IMAX (15/70)|IMAX]] version premiered at the [[Giant Screen Cinema Association]] International Conference and Trade Show in Indianapolis, Indiana, on September 22, 2009. The IMAX 3D Premiere was at the GSCA Film Expo in Los Angeles on Feb. 24, 2010.  It is available in 2D & 3D for [[70 mm film#IMAX (15/70)|15/70]] and [[70 mm film#Dynavision (8/70)|8/70]] large format film and in digital 3D.  The film has been composed with [[70 mm film#IMAX Dome (formerly OMNIMAX)|Omnimax / IMAX Domes]] in mind.  Molecules to the MAX! was nominated for Best Film Produced for the Giant Screen, Best Film for Lifelong Learning and Best Sound Design at the 2010 GSCA’s Achievement Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giantscreencinema.com/Films/FilmDatabase/FilmDatabaseDetailView/tabid/288/Default.aspx?movieid=370 |title=Giant Screen Cinema Association > Films > Film Database > FilmDatabaseDetailView |publisher=Giantscreencinema.com |date=2008-11-06 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>  Molecules to the MAX! has shown at the National Museum of Natural Science (Taichung, Taiwan) [[Maloka Museum|Maloka Interactive Museum]] (Bogata, Columbia), The Scientific Center (Salmiya, Kuwait),  [[McWane Science Center]] (Birmingham, Alabama) [[Proctor's Theatre (Schenectady, New York)|Proctor's Theatre]] (Schenectady, New York) among others.  It has been translated and versioned in [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]] and [[Arabic]]. It is distributed to Giant Screen theaters by SK Films.

=== NanoSpace ===

In the spring of 2012, the Molecularium Project launched NanoSpace, an online molecular theme park. Visitors to NanoSpace learn scientific concepts with games, activities and movies. Areas within Nanospace include the Hall of Atoms and Molecules, H2O park (the [[water cycle]]), Sizes in the Universe ([[Spatial scale|scale]] and [[scientific notation]]), Material Boulevard ([[Materials Science]]), and DNA Land ([[Molecular Biology]]).

